04156nam a22006015i 9780231539371DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014044886  a(OCoLC)984686262  a97802315393717 a10.7312/gage174042doi  a(DE-B1597)458325  a(OCoLC)908305641  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBS2506.3b.G34 2015 4aBS2506.3 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a225.92231 aGager , Jr., John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWho Made Early Christianity? :bThe Jewish Lives of the Apostle Paul /cJohn Gager , Jr.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b12 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Lectures on the History of Religions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. WAS THE APOSTLE TO THE GENTILES THE FATHER OF CHRISTIAN ANTI-JUDAISM? -- t2. THE APOSTLE PAUL IN JEWISH EYES Heretic or Hero? -- t3. LET’S MEET DOWNTOWN IN THE SYNAGOGUE Four Case Studies -- t4. TWO STORIES OF HOW EARLY CHRISTIANITY CAME TO BE -- t5. TURNING THE WORLD UPSIDE DOWN -- t6. EPILOGUE -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this historical and theological study, John G. Gager undermines the myth of the Apostle Paul's rejection of Judaism, conversion to Christianity, and founding of Christian anti-Judaism. He finds that the rise of Christianity occurred well after Paul's death and attributes the distortion of the Apostle's views to early and later Christians. Though Christian clerical elites ascribed a rejection-replacement theology to Paul's legend, Gager shows that the Apostle was considered a loyal Jew by many of his Jesus-believing contemporaries and that later Jewish and Muslim thinkers held the same view. He holds that one of the earliest misinterpretations of Paul was to name him the founder of Christianity, and in recent times numerous Jewish and Christian readers of Paul have moved beyond this understanding.Gager also finds that Judaism did not fade away after Paul's death but continued to appeal to both Christians and pagans for centuries. Jewish synagogues remained important religious and social institutions throughout the Mediterranean world. Making use of all possible literary and archaeological sources, including Muslim texts, Gager helps recover the long pre-history of a Jewish Paul, obscured by recent, negative portrayals of the Apostle, and recognizes the enduring bond between Jews and Christians that has influenced all aspects of Christianity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aChristianityxOrigin. 0aIdentification (Religion) 0aIdentification (Religion). 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/gage1740440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231539371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231539371.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles